# Research track: LLM-driven install-time semantic diversification

Successor / complement to runtime name scrambling.  Scrambles the
*implementation itself* per-device using a local code LLM instead of
just the names presented at exec time.

## Prior art
- Compiler-based MTD literature (ACM MTD workshops, 2014+)
- Polyverse Polymorphic Linux (commercial since ~2017, compile-time
  ASLR-style binary randomization — recompiles every binary with
  randomized layouts, register choices, instruction selection)
- Source-level "device diversity paradigm" papers
- Shakedown (arxiv 1810.02090): compiler-based MTD for ROP on IoT

## Differentiator
Semantic AST-level rewrites (rename, control-flow restructure,
struct-field reorder, equivalent stdlib swap) instead of just
binary-layout randomization.  Forces the attacker to fingerprint each
function independently, not just defeat ASLR.  Layers cleanly on top
of Polyverse-style binary diversification.

## Shape (≤40B-param local model + tight harness)
- AST chunker (tree-sitter, one function per chunk)
- Mutation menu (~15 semantic-preserving transforms):
    RenameLocals, SwapLoopForRecursion, ReorderStructFields,
    InvertConditional, UnrollLoop, EquivalentStdlibCall,
    SplitFunction, InlineHelper, ChangeIterationStyle, ReorderArgs,
    PromoteLocalToStatic, ReplaceMatchWithIfElse, ReorderEnumVariants,
    AddNoOpBlock, RewriteWithEquivalentControlFlow
- Per-function test extractor + cargo/pytest sandbox
- Property-test-gated infinite retry loop; fallback = keep original fn
- Reproducer: pinned seed + model produces deterministic variant
- Variant store at `.babbleon-variants/<file>.json` (seed → mutation log)

## Resource math (single 4090/5090 + 32B-class coder)
- ~50-100 tok/s
- 200k LOC ≈ 2M tokens
- Retry overhead ~2x average
- Wall clock: ~20-30 h fresh install, single-digit minutes incremental
- Matches Babbleon's weekly epoch cadence

## Why local-only
The privacy property is load-bearing.  Sending source to a frontier API
to obfuscate against attackers is a weird threat model.  Local-only
(Qwen 3 32B Coder, DeepSeek Coder, Codestral 22B class) is the honest
pitch.

## What it can do
- Function-scoped renaming + light restructure
- AST-guided mutations from a menu (not free-form)
- Property-test-gated retry loops with cheap verifiers

## What it can't do, even with infinite retries
- Whole-program algorithmic substitution across call graphs
- Multi-file planning (small model loses thread)
- Subtle behavioral preservation in concurrent code (race-introducing
  rewrites slip past tests)

## Why infinite retries help more than expected
On any given function, success probability *p* compounds:
70% success per attempt × 5 retries = 99.8% eventual success.
Fallback when retries exhaust is free — keep the original function for
that site.  60% of functions diversified + 40% original is still
substantial: attacker must fingerprint each function independently.

## Estimated build time
- Academic-grade prototype: 2-3 months, one engineer
- Production-grade (build systems, caches, deterministic seeds): 12-18 months
